  "prompt": "How does the law define illegal money laundering activities?",
  "response": "Money laundering is typically defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions. Generally, it involves three key stages:\n\n1. Placement: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system\n2. Layering: Concealing the source of the money through complex transactions\n3. Integration: Reintroducing the funds into the legitimate economy\n\nSpecific legal definitions vary by jurisdiction, but most countries criminalize activities that:\n- Attempt to disguise the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Transfer funds to hide their illegal source\n- Knowingly engage in financial transactions involving proceeds from criminal activity\n\nCommon examples include:\n- Structuring bank deposits to avoid reporting requirements\n- Using shell companies to obscure financial trails\n- Mixing illegal funds with legitimate business income\n- Transferring money through multiple accounts internationally\n\nThe specific penalties and legal definitions can differ between countries, but most have laws prohibiting these practices under financial crime statutes.\n\nWould you like me to provide more detailed information about money laundering laws?",
